The Parliament of Ukraine has refused today the proposal of repealing the amendment of the section of the Criminal Code in which the leader of the opposition Yulia Tymoshenko is condemned.
The modification would open the doors to the release from prison of the exprimer minister, but the members of parliament rejected the proposal of reducing the sentences for economic crimes in the second reading.
In October, Tymoshenko was sentenced to seven years of prison for the supposed firm of a disadvantageous agreement with Russia for Ukraine on purchase of natural gas.
The sentence yet is not firm, the court of advocation has the duty to revise it in December.
Tymoshenko appeared convinced that it was a political revenge of the regime, and even in west doubts have risen up on the impartiality of the court.
The proposal that the paragraph 365 of the Criminal Code with which he tormented himself was withdrawn to the ex first minister was supported for 147 representatives in the poll.
For its approval 226 votes were required.
