How have the prices of the journeys evolved since 1989
Up to 1989 there were five authorized state travel agencies in the Czechoslovakia of then alone: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
The travel agencies of that moment sold in most of the journey cases alone to the socialist block, for the journeys to west were very restricted.
The Czech tourists went, therefore, on holiday to the beaches of the RDA (East Germany), to the Soviet Union (Sochi in Crimea in the Black Sea) to Bulgaria and Romania (both in the Black Sea) and to Hungary (Balaton).
A positive exception was the comprised period between 1962 and 1972, when people could travel to Yugoslavia, however, the Yugoslavian regime inclined afterwards towards the west and the journeys of the Czech tourists were then quite a lot restricted.
A great paradox of the socialism was the fact that to the citizens of the socialist block (that is, also to the Checoeslovacos) was not allowed them to travel freely and individually even through the socialist countries.
If a citizen wanted to travel individually, for example, to Poland or to the Soviet Union, needed a card of invitation, if not, the individual journey was not possible.
The agencies of journey offered in those times also journeys in the West, but one had to be put to the queue with a sleeping bag and to spend like this all the night, or to have "good acquaintances" in the agency.
Still like this not everything was gained.
The called "promise of change" that was the condition for the journeys in the West, was not granted to the "politically little reliable people", that like this could not travel not at all.
The Czechoslovak coin was not a freely convertible coin and, without accountability of change, it was not possible to obtain the resources (the occidental coin) to travel to west.
The big majority of the Czechs spent its holidays in its own country, therefore there was a great number of huts and homes of summer, which the Czechs acquired. This habit still persists.
The mode of traveling from the Czechs has suffered since 1989 an authentic revolution.
Whereas up to 1989 for us it was the not goes more to pass the holidays in RDA or Bulgaria, last year the Czechs did 4.5 million journeys of holidays to countries of all the world.
Is nna great paradox, of which nowadays any longer we are not conscious, the fact that to the favorite destination at present, Croatia, up to 1989 could not be traveled freely, because was part of the Yugoslavia of then.
At the beginning of the nineties the occidental discharge from visas to travel to the adjacent States of Europe imposed itself, which provoked an enormous wave of visits of short duration, overcoat to Vienna or Germany.
The checoeslovacos, for much time, were not seen full of the excursions in the West, all the world wanted to see it to the the less for a moment.
For example, in Paris the groups of Czechs in the parks in tents slept, since our admissions of then did not allow us to pay a hotel or guesthouse.
A typical characteristic of the Czechs of that time was the to take the food (preserves, sausages, etc.) with themselves to save.
Another important moment was the introduction of the convertibility of the Czech crown, like this our tourists could finally, after decades, to buy occidental coin freely.
Our standard of living increased and with it also the average salaries, what about 1997 provoked an increase in the demand for journeys.
With the increase of the demand for journeys they started the agencies, from 1997 with regularity, to prepare the journeys using the connections of charter flights, which did to bring incredibly the prices of the journeys down in comparison with the past, thanks to the possibility to obtain discounts for the volume of passengers.
At the end of the 90 of the last century, the Czechs already traveled without visa almost to all the developed countries, except US., which still simplified more ours journeys.
Another interesting moment in the history of the post-revolutionary tourism it already happened in the 2000, when it was organized, thanks to an enormous demand, the first direct flight from Czech Republic to an exotic country, and went to Thailand.
From that year, break up all the years direct charter flights with Czech tourists did distant and hot countries. This winter it will already be blown up directly from Czech Republic to 12 exotic destinations.
The exotic countries visit them at present nearly 100 a thousand Czechs per year.
Another interesting moment of this period, which it symbolizes our post-revolutionary development, it arrived in 2008.
On 17 of November 2008, US. eliminated the visas for the Czech tourists, with what our country passed to be among the countries most developed of the world.
In 2008 the Czechs, for the first time in its history, have passed more of half of its holidays abroad (50.3%) and by first time in its history, have been used up in journeys abroad more than 15 a thousand Czech crowns for head, including the expenses in the place of stay.
