Asphalt of the UNAM would prevent holes
Rafael Herrera, investigator of the Faculty of Chemistry of the UNAM, develops asphalts modified with polymers to cause a mixture with better performance, independently of the environmental conditions and of temperature
If the signals that the pavement sends were attended to, it would not be necessary to repair nearly 200 a thousand holes every season of rains in the Metropolitan Area of the Valley of Mexico, noticed Rafael Herrera Nájera, investigator of the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) of the UNAM, who assured that if the process of construction and maintenance of an asphaltic pavement is the adequate one, the holes could be reduced in quantity or, even, be eliminated completely.
In its conference Una technological opinion of the holes, dictated within the framework of the International Year of the Chemistry, introduced that the laboratory to its charge develops asphalts modified with polymers to produce a mixture with characteristics similar to those of the asphalt, but with a bigger mechanical strength, so much to discharges as at low temperatures.
Blacksmith Nájera estimated that this type of modified asphalts could be used in places where the climate is extremely hot, as some cities of the north of the country, to improve its performance and, therefore, the formation of holes.
It explained that the asphalt, the most boring part of the oil, is an ensemble of molecules of hydrocarbons, some of high molecular weight, called asphaltenes, and others of low molecular weight, called maltenos, that joint give it to the pavement its characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
The viscoelastic behavior of the asphalt consists in that at high temperatures, near the 180 degrees, it behaves as a liquid, at 120 centigrade degrees its viscosity is very high and at 50 centigrade degrees presents an almost solid state, whereas at very low temperatures, the asphalt is returned fragile, added.
The previous means that in the streets the endurance of the asphalt is not uniform, but keeps being modified during the day according to the environmental conditions and of temperature, noticed the specialist in chemical engineering.
The investigator of the FQ observed that the streets of the City of Mexico in the main they are the last three covered by flexible pavement, which is composed of six layers of materials, of which involve to the asphalt.
Among the most superficial layers he finds the asphaltic folder, formed by small stones coated in asphalt and afterwards compacted.
Each of the piedritas that the folder constitutes, noted, is bathed with asphalt.
As the vehicles go and efforts are generated, this allows the forces to be spread very well in the pavement.
If it were modified asphalt they would still be spread better, the chemical engineer gave an opinion.
On the asphaltic folder, it abounded, a last layer folder of rolling, which is done of a fine material of stone, that is, a sand that is also coated in asphalt, called is placed.
As it is about the layer that is going to be with the plains of the vehicles in touch, it must have more mechanical force than the asphaltic folder must and provide friction in the path.
When being the part of the pavement that is going to receive and to spread the efforts, the folder of rolling requires, likewise, to have the adequate thickness and care must be taken of the material of the one that is made.
The climate, especially the humidity and the temperature variations, are also a very important factor to consider, especially the water, said, because it affects the performance of the asphaltic folder considerably.
When the ground gets damp, the water spreads in the interior of the folder and it is difficult that it goes out, this causes a softening of all the layers of the pavement and, therefore, the formation of holes.
In the process of formation of a hole, it said, the first in being worn out is the film of tread and only afterwards the asphaltic folder is affected, but the damage does not happen instantaneously, but it is a process that the first signals with adequate programs of maintenance should be attended to.
The also member of the National System of Investigators explained that the vehicular burden is another important factor in the formation of holes and, because of that, the thickness of each of the layers of the pavement must always go in relation to the vehicular burden and to guarantee that it is, to prevent holes being formed frequently.
Rafael Herrera noticed that there is still a lot that to investigate and to work on the asphalt, for example, the emulsions asphaltic, that in other countries are already even in the market and allow to repair the holes with easiness and with no need of to use high temperatures.
