Around 19% of the disabled people they are looking for an employment.
The XV Week for the employment of the disabled ones it starts today.
In spite of a solved public policy, applied since 2005, the unemployment rate among the disabled people doubles the average rate: 19%, in front of 9% for the ensemble of the population.
Discouraging?
"Not", states Éric Blanchet, chief operating officer of Adapt, the association that organizes the week for the employment of the disabled ones.
"The breakthroughs reached since fifteen years ago are considerable.
"In that then, the unemployment rate was not twice but three times higher than the average.
"However, it still remains very much because it does".
One may mention that the disabled unemployed ones keep facing numerous obstacles to access the employment.
They usually have a more advanced age: 37% has more than 50 years (17% of average).
They have a little high level of qualification: 80% has not finished the high school and, of the 2.3 million students in the superior education, so alone 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, the longstanding stop is very extended among them: 53% for the disabled ones, in front of 38% of average.
That is, there are numerous questions that obstruct especially the return to the work world and that "constitute the essence of the problem", indicates Christian Grapin, chief operating officer of Tremplin, an association created in 1992 to help the companies hire disabled workers.
Those are the objective obstacles.
Besides, there are those that are not mentioned; the mentality of the people advances, but too slowly.
A study carried out in April for the association IMS-Entreprendre for the Cité indicated that the interviewed directors have "a level of knowledge on the disabilities low", with an "excessive representation of the people in wheelchair, deficient physicists or intellectuals".
The result: the private enterprises with more than 20 workers are very far from the goal to hire 6% of disabled workers, goal that was fixed in a law of... 1987.
According to the last available ciphers, which date from 2008, they reach a relation of 2.6%.
"Now we reach about 3%", indicates Pierre Blanc, chief operating officer of Agefiph, the organism responsible for raising the contributions of the companies that do not respect this law.
The proof: the number of establishment submitted to this contribution", the same as the amounts paid out, have decreased between 2007 and 2011, passing from 59,000 to 46,000 structures (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The law of 2005, which increased the contributions, has generated a great pressure for the companies", explains Pierre Blanc.
"But this improvement also reflects a real consciousness, particularly among the great groups."
According to the Ministry of Work, so alone 59% of the societies that between 20 and 49 workers possess account with disabled employees in its staff, in front of 82% of the companies of between 100 and 199 workers.
